There can be no doubt that the Latin both here and in v. 466 is correct, although it is unusual. The old Latin writers, with Plautus among the number, used both quum and ubi as relative advs., as they originally were, and hence either indic. or subj. of any tense could be used after them, just as with a relat-ive pronoun.
